{"id": "2061", "revid": "31124876", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=2061", "title": "Winthrop", "text": "Winthrop is the innkeeper at the &lt;a href=\"Candlekeep%20Inn\"&gt;Candlekeep Inn&lt;/a&gt;. He is a friendly, tubby gentleman who enjoys giving &lt;a href=\"Gorion%27s%20Ward\"&gt;Gorion's Ward&lt;/a&gt; some playful grief and takes pride in the clean condition of his Inn. Imoen nicknamed him Puffgutts, and mentions that he is the one who taught her about keeping out of sight and such, suggesting he was a former thief.\nWithrop will still be found behind the front desk inside the inn when the party returns to &lt;a href=\"Candlekeep\"&gt;Candlekeep&lt;/a&gt; in &lt;a href=\"Chapter%20Six\"&gt;Chapter Six&lt;/a&gt; and he'll still have his witty dialogue replies. He'll be found one more time inside a small room on the &lt;a href=\"Candlekeep%20Catacombs%20Level%202\"&gt;second level&lt;/a&gt; of the &lt;a href=\"Candlekeep%20Catacombs\"&gt;Candlekeep Catacombs&lt;/a&gt;, although this time he's really a doppelganger in disguise. After a brief dialogue, the doppelganger will transform and attack.\nWhen Winthrop transforms into a doppelganger, the only changes are his hit points (30) and XP (420). He also carries one item of random treasure and he'll drop the 26 .\nDialogue.\nPrologue.\nThe first time you speak to him, the reply dialogue is based upon &lt;a href=\"reaction\"&gt;reaction&lt;/a&gt;:\n\"Well hello there, young one! Come to visit your old pal Winthrop, have ye? Well, don't forget the 10,000 gold piece book entrance fee, as per Candlekeep custom, don'tcha know.\"\nChapter Six.\nThe next time you speak to him, the reply dialogue is not based upon reaction:\n\"Aye, now there's the rapscallion! Set on the little wisp, now, and make every bolt count!\"\nCatacombs.\nThe doppelganger Winthrop will approach the party upon sight:\n\"Lost yer sense of humor, have ye? Aye, I've heard what ye've been telling all yer little friends\u2014that ol' Winthrop has a hankerin' fer a little elven arse every now and then! Heh, come here, my pretty, and I'll soon change yer mind...\""}
{"id": "8420", "revid": "47673695", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=8420", "title": "Wirthing", "text": "Wirthing is an &lt;a href=\"Iron%20Throne\"&gt;Iron Throne&lt;/a&gt; merchant who is found on the fourth floor of the &lt;a href=\"Iron%20Throne%20Headquarters\"&gt;Iron Throne Headquarters&lt;/a&gt; during the events of &lt;a href=\"Chapter%20Seven\"&gt;Chapter Seven&lt;/a&gt;. He will recognize &lt;a href=\"Gorion%27s%20Ward\"&gt;Gorion's Ward&lt;/a&gt; on sight and start a brief conversation about how &lt;a href=\"Sarevok%20Anchev\"&gt;Sarevok&lt;/a&gt; used Gorion's Ward and the Iron Throne in his plan for power in &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20%28city%29\"&gt;Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt;. When the dialogue ends, he'll quickly head for the nearest exit and disappear.\nDialogue.\n\"Why, hello &lt;Gorion's Ward&gt;. I suppose we should have expected your coming here. Bit of unfortunate business in Candlekeep, eh wot?\"\nEither dialogue option leads to the following entry in the quest section of your &lt;a href=\"Journal\"&gt;Journal&lt;/a&gt; under the title: \"The Rise of Sarevok\""}
{"id": "6269", "revid": "53053884", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=6269", "title": "Wisdom", "text": "Wisdom is one of the six &lt;a href=\"Ability%20Scores\"&gt;ability scores&lt;/a&gt;, a minimum natural score of 15 or 17 is required for cleric and druid &lt;a href=\"Classes%23Dual-class\"&gt;dual-class&lt;/a&gt; combinations.\nThis score is very important for &lt;a href=\"cleric\"&gt;cleric&lt;/a&gt;s and &lt;a href=\"druid\"&gt;druid&lt;/a&gt;s, as a high wisdom grants extra spell slots per spell level, the bonuses are cumulative, eg. a cleric with 15 wisdom will have two extra level 1 spell slots plus one extra level 2 spell slot. &lt;a href=\"Shaman\"&gt;Shaman&lt;/a&gt;s, &lt;a href=\"Ranger\"&gt;Ranger&lt;/a&gt;s and &lt;a href=\"paladin\"&gt;paladin&lt;/a&gt;s do not gain such bonus \u2013 their spell slots are determined solely by their exp level.\nThough original manuals suggest otherwise, it is worth noting that magic defence, saving throws adjustments and spell failure % are not implemented in actual gaming."}
{"id": "52958", "revid": "46775035", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=52958", "title": "Wisdom (BG3)", "text": "Wisdom (WIS) is one of the six &lt;a href=\"Ability%20Scores%20%28BG3%29\"&gt;Ability Scores&lt;/a&gt; in \"&lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20III\"&gt;Baldur's Gate III&lt;/a&gt;\". It represents a creature's senses and intuition. It affects skills checks for &lt;a href=\"Animal%20Handling%20%28BG3%29\"&gt;Animal Handling&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Insight%20%28BG3%29\"&gt;Insight&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Medicine%20%28BG3%29\"&gt;Medicine&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Perception%20%28BG3%29\"&gt;Perception&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href=\"Survival%20%28BG3%29\"&gt;Survival&lt;/a&gt;. It also affects spellcasting for &lt;a href=\"Cleric%20%28BG3%29\"&gt;Clerics&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Druid%20%28BG3%29\"&gt;Druids&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href=\"Ranger%20%28BG3%29\"&gt;Rangers&lt;/a&gt;, and is the primary attribute for Clerics and Druids."}
{"id": "6096", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=6096", "title": "Wish", "text": "Casting Wish is like gambling, as although potent, it grants random wishes.\nGeneral wish rules.\nEvery time a Wish spell is cast, a &lt;a href=\"Djinni\"&gt;Djinni&lt;/a&gt; is summoned and addresses the wizard. The player is presented with 5 possible wishes randomly selected from a pool and invited to pick one. The selected wish will be cast instantaneously, targeted on self like a &lt;a href=\"Stoneskin\"&gt;Stoneskin&lt;/a&gt; or a &lt;a href=\"Sunfire\"&gt;Sunfire&lt;/a&gt;.\nConsiderations keep in mind when reading wish descriptions:\nGameplay.\nThe &lt;a href=\"Wisdom\"&gt;Wisdom&lt;/a&gt; score of the character speaking to the Djinni determines which one of the 4 pools of wishes is used. Once the dialogue box has displayed the 5 random wishes, the player cannot back out and must select one of them.\nWisdom 18+.\nStarting from Wisdom 18, the pool of random wishes is the following. Each individual wish has a 20% chance to be one of the 5 dialogue choices every time the main Wish spell is cast.\nWisdom 15-17.\nFrom 15 to 17 Wisdom, the pool of random wishes is the following. Each individual wish has around 18% chance to be one of the 5 dialogue choices every time the main Wish spell is cast.\nWisdom 10-14.\nFrom 10 to 14 Wisdom, the pool of random wishes is the following. Each individual wish has around 18% chance to be one of the 5 dialogue choices every time the main Wish spell is cast.\nWisdom 9 and below.\nUp to 9 Wisdom, the pool of random wishes is the following. Each individual wish has around 19% chance to be one of the 5 dialogue choices every time the main Wish spell is cast.\nMod content.\nWith &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; mod installed, and especially with the \"Smarter Mages\" component, enemy spell casters do use the Wish spell against the party in certain encounters in late SoA and in ToB.\n&lt;a href=\"Spell%20Revisions\"&gt;Spell Revisions&lt;/a&gt; mod has changed this arcane spell, revising its Spell School to 'Universal\". See below:\nWish\nLevel: 9\nSchool: Universal\nRange: Personal\nDuration: Special\nCasting Time: 5\nArea of Effect: Special\nSaving Throw: None\nWish is a more potent version of the Limited Wish spell. It will fulfill literally the utterance of the spellcaster. Thus, the actuality of the past, present, or future might be altered (but possibly only for the wizard unless the wording of the spell is most carefully stated) in some limited manner. Greedy desires usually end in disaster for the wisher. The wiser the wizard, the better chance that the right wording will be chosen. Wizards with low wisdom will more often than not meet with disaster when asking for a wish."}
{"id": "51455", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=51455", "title": "Bridge's Block", "text": "Bridge's Block is a mod for &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20II\"&gt;Shadows of Amn&lt;/a&gt; that adds a new indoor location to &lt;a href=\"Athkatla\"&gt;Athkatla&lt;/a&gt;.\nIt is part of Lava Del'Vortel's \"Athkatlan Grounds\" mod series.\nOverview.\nThis mod lets the &lt;a href=\"party\"&gt;party&lt;/a&gt; enter the big stone wall in the &lt;a href=\"Bridge%20District\"&gt;Bridge District&lt;/a&gt; of &lt;a href=\"Athkatla\"&gt;Athkatla&lt;/a&gt;, and explore its inside.\nConsists of two new long indoor maps, with four small quests\nHow to get there.\nGo through the entrance in the left wall of the &lt;a href=\"Bridge%20District\"&gt;Bridge District&lt;/a&gt; (near the central arch).\nSimilar mods.\nThis mod is part of Lava Del'Vortel's \"Athkatlan Grounds\" series, which also includes these mods:\nExternal links.\n\"(For the mod's main website/forum/download page, see the infobox above.)\""}
{"id": "5662", "revid": "47673695", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=5662", "title": "Bridge District", "text": "The &lt;a href=\"Athkatla\"&gt;Athkatla&lt;/a&gt; Bridge District spans the river that separates the poor southern, and richer northern, districts. To the south is &lt;a href=\"Waukeen%27s%20Promenade\"&gt;Waukeen's Promenade&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Athkatla%20Slums\"&gt;Slums&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Athkatla%20Docks\"&gt;Docks&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Athkatla%20Graveyard\"&gt;Graveyard&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Athkatla%20City%20Gates\"&gt;City Gates&lt;/a&gt;; to the north, the &lt;a href=\"Temple%20District\"&gt;Temple&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Athkatla%20Government\"&gt;Government Districts&lt;/a&gt;.\nLt. Aegisfield and the \"Skinner\" murders.\nThe very first time the party tries to cross the Athkatla Bridge, they are unavoidably intercepted by &lt;a href=\"Lieutenant%20Aegisfield\"&gt;Lieutenant Aegisfield&lt;/a&gt;. He will warn everyone about murders occurring here, which begins the district's very first &lt;a href=\"Quests\"&gt;side quest&lt;/a&gt;, providing the option to &lt;a href=\"Solve%20the%20%22skinner%22%20murders%20in%20the%20Bridge%20District\"&gt;locate and confront those responsible&lt;/a&gt;. More comments and outcries from concerned citizens are heard when you observe the latest adjacent crime scene.\nGameplay.\nThe potential companion &lt;a href=\"Neera\"&gt;Neera&lt;/a&gt; is introduced into the BG2EE campaign in this district. If you have moved through the whole area, and then retrace your path back to the location where you first encountered Lt. Aggesfield, then a scene will automatically play out for the party. Afterwards, When the party leaves and moves from the Bridge District to another area, the rest of her introduction will continue in a \"between\" area. See Neera's link for further information.\nContainers.\nThere are seven containers in this district; none have locks, traps or alarms:\nMod content.\nThe &lt;a href=\"Quest%20Pack\"&gt;Quest Pack&lt;/a&gt; mod adds the \"Infernal Thievery\" questline, which happens in the bridge district. \nThe &lt;a href=\"Check%20the%20Bodies%20%28CtB%29\"&gt;Check the Bodies (CtB)&lt;/a&gt; mod and the &lt;a href=\"Of%20Elves%20and%20Artifacts\"&gt;Of Elves and Artifacts&lt;/a&gt; module will begin in the Bridge District if one of your party contains a Bard, Sorcerer or Mage. The PC must also have taken on a Stronghold as well.\n&lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; will make mostly AI changes to opponents encountered in the Bridge district, such as the Muggers, Vampires, the Storehouse, Neb and almost all creatures of any tactical note."}
