{"id": "28898", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=28898", "title": "Cania", "text": "Cania is a &lt;a href=\"dryad\"&gt;dryad&lt;/a&gt; found on the first floor of &lt;a href=\"Irenicus%27s%20Dungeon%201st%20Floor\"&gt;Irenicus's Dungeon&lt;/a&gt;. She and two of her fellow dryads, &lt;a href=\"Elyme\"&gt;Elyme&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Ulene\"&gt;Ulene&lt;/a&gt;, have been trapped by &lt;a href=\"Jon%20Irenicus\"&gt;Jon Irenicus&lt;/a&gt; in the Dryad Grotto that's located between Irenicus's master bedroom and &lt;a href=\"Ellesime\"&gt;Ellesime&lt;/a&gt;'s bedroom. \nWhen you get near them, they will speak to you and &lt;a href=\"Helping%20Irenicus%27s%20captive%20dryads\"&gt;ask you to retrieve&lt;/a&gt; their &lt;a href=\"acorns\"&gt;acorns&lt;/a&gt; from the duergar clan leader &lt;a href=\"Ilyich\"&gt;Ilyich&lt;/a&gt; and give them to the &lt;a href=\"Vaelasa\"&gt;Fairy Queen&lt;/a&gt; in the &lt;a href=\"Windspear%20Hills\"&gt;Windspear Hills&lt;/a&gt; area. Doing this will free the dryads from their captivity. If you kill the dryad instead, the Fairy Queen will know about this and attack you when she sees you.\nIf you have already &lt;a href=\"Free%20the%20Djinn\"&gt;dealt with the djinn&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Malaaq\"&gt;Malaaq&lt;/a&gt; and are searching for his &lt;a href=\"The%20Genie%27s%20Flask\"&gt;flask&lt;/a&gt;, they will offer to give you the flask if you promise to take their acorns to the Fairy Queen."}
{"id": "20996", "revid": "209199", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=20996", "title": "Canon", "text": "Discussion of Canon in the \"Baldur's Gate\" game universe often revolves around the so-called \"canon party\" that travels with &lt;a href=\"Gorion%27s%20Ward\"&gt;Gorion's Ward&lt;/a&gt; during the events of &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20%28game%29\"&gt;Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt;, , and .\nIn some contexts \"canon\" can also refer to &lt;a href=\"%23Forgotten%20Realms%20canon\"&gt;Forgotten Realms canon&lt;/a&gt;.\nCanon party.\nBaldur's Gate.\n establishes in its introduction that &lt;a href=\"Gorion%27s%20Ward\"&gt;Gorion's Ward&lt;/a&gt; was captured along with &lt;a href=\"Imoen\"&gt;Imoen&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Khalid\"&gt;Khalid&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Jaheira\"&gt;Jaheira&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Minsc\"&gt;Minsc&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Dynaheir\"&gt;Dynaheir&lt;/a&gt;. While the player is allowed to speak with various members of the &lt;a href=\"party\"&gt;party&lt;/a&gt; as if they do not remember them, this is employed as a method to give players a brief summary of the events of the first game, and does not seem intended as a way for the player to dispute their past connections with these characters.\nHowever, it is not made clear whether Gorion's Ward traveled with these &lt;a href=\"companions\"&gt;companions&lt;/a&gt; \"exclusively\" throughout their adventures in &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20%28game%29\"&gt;Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt;, only that they traveled together for some amount of time. Jaheira's introductory dialogue to a player who claims not to remember her states that \"we have traveled together for some time, and the places we have gone number too many to name,\" so it's not unreasonable to assume that a lot of time was spent with Jaheira and Khalid at least, but still no definite conclusions can be drawn. No returning party members in Baldur's Gate II except Imoen make any reference to being present for the slaying of &lt;a href=\"Sarevok%20Anchev\"&gt;Sarevok&lt;/a&gt; at the conclusion of Baldur's Gate.\nTherefore it cannot be stated definitively that Baldur's Gate II establishes a canon party for the first game, but it is not out of the question to accept the returning characters as such.\nOne other note on the subject of canon for Baldur's Gate is that many possible companions from the first game do return in Baldur's Gate II as non-playable characters. It could be considered canon that those characters did not die permanently even if the player killed them or allowed them to die in the first game. The player is even sometimes able to comment on this, e.g. \"didn't you die?\" An example of returning characters like these are &lt;a href=\"Xzar\"&gt;Xzar&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Montaron\"&gt;Montaron&lt;/a&gt;.\nTales of the Sword Coast.\nThe original release of the included a pre-existing save file called the Mission Pack Save, intended to allow players to skip the content of Baldur's Gate and play the new content directly. This file has never been included with . The active party members included in this save file are &lt;a href=\"Abdel%20Adrian\"&gt;Abdel Adrian&lt;/a&gt; as a &lt;a href=\"fighter\"&gt;fighter&lt;/a&gt;, Imoen, Jaheira, Minsc, &lt;a href=\"Edwin%20Odesseiron\"&gt;Edwin&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href=\"Viconia%20DeVir\"&gt;Viconia&lt;/a&gt;. Khalid and Dynaheir are not present and no attempt is made to explain their absence.\nAgain, the introduction of Baldur's Gate II only establishes that the party members met at the beginning had traveled together for some time, and not necessarily on an exclusive basis. This save could be seen as contributing to the list of characters Gorion's Ward traveled with at some point, but is far from a definitive source. It is equally likely that it simply represented a well-rounded party the developers thought were well-equipped for the challenges in the expansion, though it is notable that both Edwin and Viconia make a reappearance in &lt;a href=\"Athkatla\"&gt;Athkatla&lt;/a&gt; in Baldur's Gate II.\nBaldur's Gate: Siege of Dragonspear.\n will import any party of characters from Baldur's Gate, allowing players to treat any combination of them as canon -- at least for the &lt;a href=\"Korlasz%20Family%20Tomb\"&gt;introductory dungeon&lt;/a&gt;.\nWith the exception of Imoen, Siege is very careful in allowing the player to treat every other returning companion as a complete stranger or old friend. The initial conversation choice with each of them establishes this, and further dialogue is written to reinforce that choice. The player is even allowed to deny having traveled with Jaheira, who Gorion's Ward is guaranteed to have at least heard about from &lt;a href=\"Gorion\"&gt;Gorion&lt;/a&gt;. More than any other game, Siege goes out of its way to deny any particular canon party, allowing each player to make that determination for themselves. This may conflict with Baldur's Gate II's introduction, though at least every character from that introduction can be incorporated into the party in Siege of Dragonspear (along with later returning characters Edwin and Viconia).\nShadows of Amn.\n&lt;a href=\"Irenicus%27s%20Dungeon\"&gt;Irenicus's Dungeon&lt;/a&gt; in the introduction of allows Gorion's Ward to recruit Imoen, Minsc, Jaheira, and &lt;a href=\"Yoshimo\"&gt;Yoshimo&lt;/a&gt;, but the player is also allowed to reject or ignore any of these companions. While it seems likely that the player is intended to take these companions along, Baldur's Gate II does not enforce any particular party, and there are not yet any game sources set post-BGII that make any declaration one way or the other.\nIt makes sense to consider Yoshimo a likely replacement &lt;a href=\"thief\"&gt;thief&lt;/a&gt; for Imoen, and the relative significance of his personal quest that takes place at &lt;a href=\"Spellhold\"&gt;Spellhold&lt;/a&gt; could be seen as an indicator that he would likely have traveled with Gorion's Ward, but again, the game is flexible in allowing the player to make their own determinations on this front. &lt;a href=\"Jan%20Jansen\"&gt;Jan Jansen&lt;/a&gt; is just as likely to have been the party's \"canon thief\" as Yoshimo, until some future source materializes that establishes a definitive answer.\nAlong these same lines, it is tempting to include &lt;a href=\"Sarevok%20Anchev\"&gt;Sarevok&lt;/a&gt; as a canon party member in , due to his relative plot significance, extensive dialogues, and personal quest taking place there. However, like other characters as established previously, Gorion's Ward is not required to take him along.\nGiven the through line of characters across all games in the series, it would not be unreasonable to look at Gorion's Ward, Imoen, Jaheira, Minsc, and Sarevok as a likely party concluding events in Throne of Bhaal. The fact that the player is able to take most of these characters from the beginning of Baldur's Gate all the way to the end is a reasonable argument toward potential status as canon. But players are still allowed to form their own party at any stage across all games, and no source exists yet that might judge any of them incorrect or non-canon. The upcoming &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20III\"&gt;Baldur's Gate III&lt;/a&gt; may eventually provide some answers on this front.\nCanon Gorion's Ward.\nThe &lt;a href=\"Prologue\"&gt;Prologue&lt;/a&gt; narration in Baldur's Gate establishes Gorion's Ward to be about 20 years old. While some races in Forgotten Realms are much longer-lived than others, this age does not preclude any particular racial choice, since most of them mature at roughly the same rate as &lt;a href=\"human\"&gt;human&lt;/a&gt;s. As one example, &lt;a href=\"Elf\"&gt;elves&lt;/a&gt; are not considered adults until they reach the age of 110, but they grow physically throughout their childhood years much the same as humans. A 20-year-old elf would be considered immature by elf standards, but having been raised by Gorion, would have the same level of education and understanding of the world that any other race would have in that environment. In Gorion's chamber in Candlekeep there is a note stating \"I am not your biological father.\" This means the protagonist must be human or half-elf. As you would already know you were not biologically related if you were not human as Gorion is Human.\n&lt;a href=\"Half-orc\"&gt;Half-orc&lt;/a&gt; was not an option as a playable race in the original release of Baldur's Gate, and they are described as merely being \"tolerated\" in &lt;a href=\"Amn\"&gt;Amn&lt;/a&gt;, so it isn't unreasonable to conclude that a half-orc Gorion's Ward would be unlikely. Purists who look only to the original release for canon certainly would discard this race as an option.\nIf nothing else, humans are among the most widespread and common of all the races in Forgotten Realms.\nIf a canon &lt;a href=\"alignment\"&gt;alignment&lt;/a&gt; must be determined for Gorion's Ward, it seems most likely the character would be Chaotic. As the prophecies of Alaundo state:\n\"During the days of the Avatars, the Lord of Murder will spawn a score of mortal progeny. These offspring will be aligned good and evil, but chaos will flow through them all. \"\nThat chaos may be paired with good or neutral, as many of the Ward's, most likely, companions are good or neutral, and neutral good Imoen is a constant presence throughout the series; it seems unlikely that a good-aligned friend would remain a companion or even stand by and watch as the Ward committed numerous evil acts. Jaheira's introductory dialogue at the start of Baldur's Gate II states that \"our exploits together have left the land for the better,\" which is the clearest indication of the way Gorion's Ward behaved during Baldur's Gate at least. Much of the games' content is also heavily skewed toward committing good acts, even if for selfish reasons. Finally, there are indications in the prologue and by later characters who knew him that Gorion would have raised his Ward to be a good person.\nThere is no indication of a canon gender. If one were to assume that a romance needed to take place in canon, it is notable that there are fewer options for female Wards than males.\nThe games do not indicate a canon &lt;a href=\"Classes\"&gt;class&lt;/a&gt; for Gorion's Ward. There are some considerations and guesses that can be made based on the few established facts about this character.\nThere is nothing that would preclude any multiclass or dual class combinations.\nForgotten Realms canon.\nBaldur's Gate series game takes place in &lt;a href=\"Forgotten%20Realms\"&gt;Forgotten Realms&lt;/a&gt; Dungeon &amp; Dragons setting, so areas and events in game fits the Forgotten Realm canon."}
{"id": "7971", "revid": "4896558", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=7971", "title": "Canticle", "text": "Canticle is one of many slaves found in the &lt;a href=\"Cloakwood%20Mines\"&gt;Cloakwood Mines&lt;/a&gt; during \"&lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20%28game%29\"&gt;Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt;\". He claims to have been a bard once, but the harsh conditions of the mine have ruined his lungs and his voice.\nLike most slaves in the area, he merely serves to help reinforce the setting and their predicament; in Canticle's case, his dialogue reinforces &lt;a href=\"Gorion%27s%20Ward\"&gt;Gorion's Ward&lt;/a&gt; likely target - &lt;a href=\"Davaeorn\"&gt;Davaeorn&lt;/a&gt; - while making the point that there's even more to be investigated."}
{"id": "38124", "revid": "773742", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=38124", "title": "Canyon Ambush", "text": "The Canyon Ambush is a in \"\".\nThe ambush is automatically triggered when and their party leaves the &lt;a href=\"Coalition%20Camp\"&gt;Coalition Camp&lt;/a&gt; and travels anywhere for the first time. It consists of four mercenaries under the watchful eye of a &lt;a href=\"Shadowy%20Figure\"&gt;Shadowy Figure&lt;/a&gt; whilst passing through a canyon that is a dead magic zone.\nOnce at least two mercenaries die, if still alive, the Shadowy Figure will attempt to hide and leave the map, taking his gear.\nTreasure.\nThe precise amount of lootable ammunition recovered will depend on how quickly the ranged attackers are slain, as will the number of potions; the faster the enemy mercenaries are defeated, the more potions will be left, as they will readily use these to heal themselves and survive longer."}
{"id": "29771", "revid": "31124876", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=29771", "title": "Captain (Firkraag's Maze)", "text": "This Captain is a &lt;a href=\"wolfwere\"&gt;wolfwere&lt;/a&gt; who is found in the cave area that's located within the northwest section of &lt;a href=\"Firkraag%27s%20Maze\"&gt;Firkraag's Maze&lt;/a&gt;. He is in the process of berating an orc named &lt;a href=\"Gerg\"&gt;Gerg&lt;/a&gt; and an unnamed small &lt;a href=\"troll\"&gt;troll&lt;/a&gt; about their failure to satisfactorily clean &lt;a href=\"Firkraag\"&gt;Firkraag&lt;/a&gt;'s golems.\nFollowing a brief dialogue between the three, the Captain will transform into his wolfwere form and attack the orc and troll, concentrating on Gerg first. The outcome of this battle has three possibilities:\nIt is also possible for the party to intervene in the battle:\nIf you attack the orc and troll but the wolfwere is killed, they will attack the party since attacking either of them during the battle turns both of them hostile."}
{"id": "56194", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=56194", "title": "Captain (githyanki)", "text": "The Captain is a &lt;a href=\"Githyanki%20%28Race%29\"&gt;Githyanki (Race)&lt;/a&gt; pseudo-mage/warrior encountered in &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20II%20Chapter%206\"&gt;Baldur's Gate II Chapter 6&lt;/a&gt; in one of Athkatla's districts if the party is in possession of the &lt;a href=\"Silver%20Blade\"&gt;Silver Blade&lt;/a&gt;.\nThe captain will teleport in (as well as other githyanki) at the behest of the &lt;a href=\"Kruin\"&gt;Kruin&lt;/a&gt;, if the party refuses to return the blade to him.\nGameplay.\nThis captain is a two-handed sword and plate mail clad creature that engages in melee combat with the closest enemy it can detect.\nWhen the creature first arrives, it launches the preparatory buff chain shown on the InfoBox, but that's all the spells it can do, and for some reason, this githyanki has no &lt;a href=\"Psionic%20Ability\"&gt;Psionic Ability&lt;/a&gt;.\nEven with the &lt;a href=\"Haste\"&gt;Haste&lt;/a&gt; spell applied, the captain's attacks per round will only be 2. \nThis captain is lacking in martial sword prowess and won't be able to really threaten a chapter 6 party member, most likely.\nThe captain is scripted to try and quaff its potion for healing purposes when heavily wounded.\nMod content.\nThe &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; makes some revisions to the captain.\nThe captain is redesigned as a level 10/10 &lt;a href=\"Fighter%20/%20Mage\"&gt;Fighter / Mage&lt;/a&gt;, with a new set of AI scripts for smarter tactical behavior and spell/ability use.\nThe creature is scripted to use its \"Planar travel\" and \"Psionic Mind Blast\" abilities.\nA new spell book of memorized wizard spells is furnished, with scripted use of all the spells based on tactical criteria and enemy protections/vulnerabilities.\nThe captain's initial preparatory buff chain might include &lt;a href=\"Mirror%20Image\"&gt;Mirror Image&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Haste\"&gt;Haste&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Minor%20Globe%20of%20Invulnerability\"&gt;Minor Globe of Invulnerability&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Shield%20%28spell%29\"&gt;Shield (spell)&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Ghost%20Armor\"&gt;Ghost Armor&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href=\"Stoneskin\"&gt;Stoneskin&lt;/a&gt;.\nA &lt;a href=\"Minor%20Sequencer\"&gt;Minor Sequencer&lt;/a&gt; is readied for instant release.\nSeveral potions are carried to boost abilities and heal wounds.\nThe creature's melee combat abilities are slightly better, but not by much, and it is focused on spell casting damage dealing and disabling spells rather than swordplay.\nNote that the mod changes the Plate mail worn by the creature to an undroppable version that allows spell casting of wizard spells."}
{"id": "56187", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=56187", "title": "Captain (githyanki WK)", "text": "The Captain is a &lt;a href=\"Githyanki%20%28Race%29\"&gt;Githyanki (Race)&lt;/a&gt; pseudo-mage/warrior/psionicist found on the &lt;a href=\"Watcher%27s%20Keep%20Githyanki%20Encampment\"&gt;Watcher's Keep Githyanki Encampment&lt;/a&gt;, during the and games.\nGameplay.\nThis githyanki, armed with the legendary &lt;a href=\"Angurvadal\"&gt;Angurvadal&lt;/a&gt; blade of yore, will shout the alarm to repel the party, as they are viewed as invaders in their lair.\nThe githyaki captain is the de facto leader of this encampment and will be hostile.\nThe creature is scripted to be able to employ several unique &lt;a href=\"Psionic%20Ability\"&gt;Psionic Ability&lt;/a&gt; powers that are only encountered from this particular creature. See the InfoBox for links.\nThe creature will defend himself and attack in melee combat and psionics to any within range.\nIf able, the captain will quaff a potion to heal itself at a certain damage threshold.\nWhen defeated, the party should recover the marvelous sword he wielded and peruse the information in the scraps of writing he carried.\nMod content.\nThe &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; makes some revisions to the captain.\nIt changes its class to paladin with a &lt;a href=\"blackguard\"&gt;blackguard&lt;/a&gt; kit. His experience level is raised to 25, and strength attribute is 22 (to approximate having buffed with Angurvadal).\nWeapon proficiencies are now 2 pips in Longsword, and 2 pips in single weapon fighting style, so &lt;a href=\"THAC0\"&gt;THAC0&lt;/a&gt;, damage, and attacks per round will be much better, as well as armor class.\nAs a blackguard he's scripted to utilize &lt;a href=\"Absorb%20Health\"&gt;Absorb Health&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Aura%20of%20Despair\"&gt;Aura of Despair&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Poison%20Weapon\"&gt;Poison Weapon&lt;/a&gt;.\n&lt;a href=\"Psionic%20Ability\"&gt;Psionic Ability&lt;/a&gt; use includes all the abilities from the base creature, plus &lt;a href=\"Psionic%20Maze\"&gt;Psionic Maze&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Ballistic%20Attack\"&gt;Ballistic Attack&lt;/a&gt;, Psionic Blur and Planar Travel.\nThe blackguard has use of several &lt;a href=\"High-level%20class%20ability\"&gt;HLA's&lt;/a&gt; including &lt;a href=\"Whirlwind%20Attack\"&gt;Whirlwind Attack&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Greater%20Whirlwind%20Attack\"&gt;Greater Whirlwind Attack&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Hardiness\"&gt;Hardiness&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Summon%20Fallen%20Deva\"&gt;Summon Fallen Deva&lt;/a&gt;.\nAnd finally, two potions are retained for scripted for use to boost abilities and heal wounds."}
{"id": "55058", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=55058", "title": "Captain Aduo'on", "text": "Captain Aduo'on is a male elf fighter encountered in the city of &lt;a href=\"Suldanessellar\"&gt;Suldanessellar&lt;/a&gt; during &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20II%20Chapter%207\"&gt;Baldur's Gate II Chapter 7&lt;/a&gt;.\nGameplay.\nThe captain is located with a few &lt;a href=\"Wounded%20Elf\"&gt;Wounded Elves&lt;/a&gt; and the healer &lt;a href=\"Reirra\"&gt;Reirra&lt;/a&gt;, not too far from &lt;a href=\"The%20Palace\"&gt;The Palace&lt;/a&gt; gate ahead. Apparently, there was a big push to liberate the palace by the elves that cost many lives, and the elves were beaten back by the invaders.\nSpeaking with the captain can fill-in the party of the location of \"The Exile\", and potentially where queen &lt;a href=\"Ellesime\"&gt;Ellesime&lt;/a&gt; is as well.\nConversation can lead to an update to the &lt;a href=\"Getting%20inside%20the%20palace%20in%20Suldanessellar\"&gt;Getting inside the palace in Suldanessellar&lt;/a&gt;. The party learns that &lt;a href=\"Jon%20Irenicus\"&gt;Jon Irenicus&lt;/a&gt; flew over the city and landed in a clearing to the northwest astride a black dragon.\nThe captain urges the party to get inside the palace quickly before things get out of hand. His forces are getting depleted quickly and can't break through without help.\nAfter the &lt;a href=\"Avatar%20of%20Rillifane\"&gt;Avatar of Rillifane&lt;/a&gt; is awakened, and the &lt;a href=\"Elven%20Spirit\"&gt;Elven Spirit&lt;/a&gt; guardians of Rillifane have purged the enemy from the city streets - the captain has some congratulatory comments about this.\nMod content.\nInstallation of the &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; revises the captain's weapon proficiencies commensurate with a level 20 fighter, and assigns &lt;a href=\"High-level%20class%20ability\"&gt;High-level class ability&lt;/a&gt; scripted use.\nThree potions are available for scripted use to boost abilities and heal damage."}
{"id": "51898", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=51898", "title": "Captain Alyittyl", "text": "Captain Alyittyl is a &lt;a href=\"sahuagin\"&gt;sahuagin&lt;/a&gt; located in the &lt;a href=\"City%20of%20Caverns\"&gt;City of Caverns&lt;/a&gt; in \"Shadows of Amn \"campaign.\nGameplay.\nThis Warrior captain is nearby &lt;a href=\"King%20Ixilthetocal\"&gt;King Ixilthetocal&lt;/a&gt;. \nIf for any reason that the party is in combat with the Captain, the creature will behave as a crossbow and spear wielding fighting opponent. \nMod content.\nThe &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; mod makes some changes. It provides a tactical AI script for smarter combat behavior. The captain is assigned a level 12 Fighter class. The crossbow and bolts are removed, and the creature concentrates in spear combat, with grand mastery weapon proficiency and 2 pips in two-handed fighting style. A &lt;a href=\"Potion%20of%20Magic%20Shielding\"&gt;Potion of Magic Shielding&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Potion%20of%20Extra%20Healing\"&gt;Potion of Extra Healing&lt;/a&gt; are scripted for quaffing. The creature has a new +2 Spear weapon that applies a &lt;a href=\"Poison\"&gt;Poison&lt;/a&gt; effect on any hit. Save vs. Death to negate or take 2 damage/sec for 15 seconds."}
{"id": "47994", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=47994", "title": "Captain Arat", "text": "Captain Arat is the garrison commander for the &lt;a href=\"de%27Arnise%20Keep\"&gt;de'Arnise Keep&lt;/a&gt;. He is found in the small fort that is located next to the keep. Talking to him will provide the party with a better understanding of what they will face once they get inside. He'll also mention the secret side entrance to the keep and offer to help with the fighting if you are able to quickly get the drawbridge lowered.\nIf &lt;a href=\"Nalia%20de%27Arnise\"&gt;Nalia&lt;/a&gt; isn't in the party, he'll give a brief synopsis of what will happen to the keep were she to die. He'll also mention that the only way to kill a &lt;a href=\"troll\"&gt;troll&lt;/a&gt; is with fire or acid.\nIf Nalia is in the party, he'll reiterate the troll killing tip given by her when you first arrive in the area and he'll also give you 20 &lt;a href=\"Arrow%20of%20Fire\"&gt;arrows of fire&lt;/a&gt;.\nIf Nalia dies during the fight to reclaim the keep, he'll tell you to have her restored immediately to prevent the &lt;a href=\"Lord%20Farthington%20Roenall\"&gt;Roenall&lt;/a&gt; family from taking control of the keep and it's surrounding lands. This is a necessary thing to accomplish if you want to finish &lt;a href=\"The%20de%27Arnise%20Keep%20has%20been%20Invaded\"&gt;The de'Arnise Keep has been Invaded&lt;/a&gt; quest and to make the keep your &lt;a href=\"Ruling%20the%20de%27Arnise%20Keep%20and%20Lands\"&gt;stronghold&lt;/a&gt; if you satisfy the &lt;a href=\"class\"&gt;class&lt;/a&gt; requirements."}
{"id": "48023", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=48023", "title": "Captain Cernick", "text": "Captain Cernick is the new Keep garrison commander of the guard for the &lt;a href=\"de%27Arnise%20Keep\"&gt;de'Arnise Keep&lt;/a&gt;. \nGameplay.\nHe first appears as just a guard in the courtyard (along with three &lt;a href=\"de%27Arnise%20Guard\"&gt;guards&lt;/a&gt;, two &lt;a href=\"Giant%20Troll\"&gt;giant trolls&lt;/a&gt;, and a &lt;a href=\"Greater%20Yuan-ti\"&gt;greater yuan-ti&lt;/a&gt;) when the drawbridge is lowered during the &lt;a href=\"The%20de%27Arnise%20Keep%20has%20been%20Invaded\"&gt;liberation&lt;/a&gt; of the keep from &lt;a href=\"TorGal\"&gt;TorGal&lt;/a&gt; and his pack of &lt;a href=\"troll\"&gt;troll&lt;/a&gt;s.\nAfter the liberation of the keep, he is found standing in the courtyard if &lt;a href=\"Gorion%27s%20Ward\"&gt;Gorion's Ward&lt;/a&gt; has met the &lt;a href=\"class\"&gt;class&lt;/a&gt; qualifications to take on the keep as a &lt;a href=\"stronghold\"&gt;stronghold&lt;/a&gt;. Captain Cernick has taken on the duties of &lt;a href=\"Captain%20Arat\"&gt;Captain Arat&lt;/a&gt; who retired after the keep was liberated. As captain of the guard, he is then involved in two of the problems that must be dealt with by Gorion's Ward in the capacity as &lt;a href=\"Ruling%20the%20de%27Arnise%20Keep%20and%20Lands\"&gt;ruler&lt;/a&gt; of the keep."}
{"id": "44436", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=44436", "title": "Captain Dennis", "text": "Captain Dennis is the commander of the &lt;a href=\"Mercenary%20of%20Riatavin\"&gt;Mercenaries of Riatavin&lt;/a&gt; and part of the &lt;a href=\"Limited%20Wish%20Adventure\"&gt;Limited Wish Adventure&lt;/a&gt;. He is initially found on the second floor of &lt;a href=\"Delosar%27s%20Inn\"&gt;Delosar's Inn&lt;/a&gt; in the &lt;a href=\"Bridge%20District\"&gt;Bridge District&lt;/a&gt; of Athkatla. The captain is accompanied by four other mercenaries.\nGameplay.\nHe initiates conversation when you enter Delosar's Inn. If you provoke him he will attack you, thus rendering you unable to do the quest.\nCaptain Dennis is scripted to:\n-Use his Potion of Frost Giant Strength if an enemy is within sight (can be pickpocketed to prevent this).\n-Use his Potion of Extra Healing when below 20% hp (can also be pickpocketed).\n-Equip a ranged weapon when there are no enemies close to him (his crossbow, which is marked as \"unstealable\").\n-And equip a melee weapon when an enemy gets close (the Boomerang Dagger, in melee mode, if it hasn't been pickpocketed; otherwise, he'll use his halberd, which is marked as \"unstealable\").\nAs a level 16 Fighter, Dennis can be quite formidable, but fighting him from a distance can make it easier to take him down, as he has 5 APR when using either of his melee weapons, but only 3 APR when using his crossbow. Plus, the extra strength he gets from the Potion of Frost Giant Strength has no effect on his abilities when he's wielding his crossbow.\nMod content.\nThe &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; revises some aspects of Captain Dennis. An SCS Fighter AI script is assigned for better tactical behavior and potion use. The Captain will use healing potions during the battle when HP falls below a certain threshold and quaff his Potion of Frost Giant Strength. The creature favors Halberd use in melee range, and most likely won't utilize the crossbow or boomerang dagger unless no opponents are close to him or are moving away from him. \nIn terms of weapon proficiencies and SCS, and the Mod's mantra to not \"cheat\" with abilities, Captain Dennis as a level 16 Fighter can by rule only have 9 proficiency points. In the unmodded game he has grandmastery in all weapons, which is technically impossible. With SCS, he is assigned 4 pips in Halberd, 4 pips in dagger and 1 pip in crossbow. So, in this sense, he actually has a slightly reduced APR and damage output with his halberd and dagger. His crossbow attack will suffer a marked decrease in effectiveness, but he really doesn't use it with SCS either."}
{"id": "6250", "revid": "47673695", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=6250", "title": "Captain Egeissag", "text": "Captain Egeissag is a male &lt;a href=\"drow\"&gt;drow&lt;/a&gt; and a captain of &lt;a href=\"Sendai\"&gt;Sendai&lt;/a&gt;'s drow forces in &lt;a href=\"Sendai%27s%20Enclave\"&gt;her enclave&lt;/a&gt;. In &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20II%20Chapter%209\"&gt;Chapter 9&lt;/a&gt;, when you reach Egeissag in &lt;a href=\"Sendai%27s%20Enclave\"&gt;Sendai's Enclave&lt;/a&gt; you will be challenged to a one-on-one pit fight. If you refuse you will have to fight him and his hard to reach drow warriors. On his corpse is the &lt;a href=\"Bowstring%20of%20Gond\"&gt;Bowstring of Gond&lt;/a&gt;, two &lt;a href=\"Potions%20of%20Superior%20Healing\"&gt;Potions of Superior Healing&lt;/a&gt;, one &lt;a href=\"Drow%20Elven%20Chain\"&gt;Drow Elven Chain&lt;/a&gt;, and two &lt;a href=\"Drow%20Scimitar\"&gt;Drow Scimitar&lt;/a&gt;."}
{"id": "50206", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=50206", "title": "Captain Erelon", "text": "Captain Erelon is hired by &lt;a href=\"Balthazar\"&gt;Balthazar&lt;/a&gt; as part of the Army he is building in his conflict with the other Bhaalspawn. He appears to be overseeing a drill for five &lt;a href=\"Mercenary%20%28Archer%29\"&gt;Mercenary (Archer)&lt;/a&gt; soldiers. The captain occasionally summons a creature for the Archers to aim for and slay (such as an Umberhulk). If you initiate talk with the captain, he impatiently says dismissive things to get you to stop bothering him. If you keep interrupting Captain Erelon again, or say the wrong thing, the entire group and the captain will become hostile, and start their target practice on you instead.\nCaptain Erelon has no weapon proficiencies assigned (yet another oversight?). In melee he wields a Two-handed sword +2, and will cast some spells, if given enough distance he employs the &lt;a href=\"Darkfire%20Bow\"&gt;Darkfire Bow&lt;/a&gt; and fires normal arrows. \nMod Content.\nInstallation of the &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; Mod makes some changes to Captain Erelon. First, He gets a SCS revised script. Also, the Mod fills up the captain's spell book commensurate with a level 16 mage. SCS spell triggers and sequencers are added. Weapon proficiency and fighting style pips are added to go along with the creature's melee and bow weapon (2 pips) in short bow, Two-handed sword and Two-handed weapon style. Random treasures are added to the inventory. If the &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Revisions\"&gt;Spell Revisions&lt;/a&gt; Mod is also installed, then that Mods spells will be used by the captain."}
{"id": "51902", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=51902", "title": "Captain Feerlattiys", "text": "Captain Feerlattiys is a &lt;a href=\"sahuagin\"&gt;sahuagin&lt;/a&gt; located in the &lt;a href=\"City%20of%20Caverns\"&gt;City of Caverns&lt;/a&gt; in \"Shadows of Amn \"campaign.\nGameplay.\nThis Warrior captain is nearby &lt;a href=\"Royal%20High%20Priestess%20Senityili\"&gt;Royal High Priestess Senityili&lt;/a&gt;. He also arrests and escorts &lt;a href=\"High%20Priestess%20Tlyysixxous\"&gt;High Priestess Tlyysixxous&lt;/a&gt; for sacrifice to Sekolah, due to an unacceptable voiced opinion not shared by &lt;a href=\"King%20Ixilthetocal\"&gt;King Ixilthetocal&lt;/a&gt;. \nIf for any reason that the party is in combat with the captain, the creature will behave as a crossbow and spear wielding fighting opponent. \nMod content.\nThe &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; mod makes some significant changes - almost a new creature entirely. It provides a tactical AI script for smarter combat behavior. The captain is assigned a level 18 Fighter class. The creature concentrates in spear combat, with grand mastery weapon proficiency and 2 pips in two-handed fighting style. Strength is boosted to 20 and HP to 80. APR, THAC0 and damage are thus improved. Saving throws are improved.\nThe creature has a new undroppable +2 Spear weapon that applies a &lt;a href=\"Poison\"&gt;Poison&lt;/a&gt; effect on any hit. Save vs. Death to negate or take 2 damage/sec for 15 seconds. Various potions are scripted for quaffing."}
{"id": "36095", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=36095", "title": "Captain Haegan", "text": "Captain Haegan is the leader of a slaver outfit that operates out of the &lt;a href=\"Slaver%20Stockade\"&gt;Slaver Stockade&lt;/a&gt; in the &lt;a href=\"Athkatla%20Slums\"&gt;Slums District&lt;/a&gt;. He is found in the storage room along with a &lt;a href=\"Priest%20of%20Cyric%20%28Slaver%20Stockade%29\"&gt;Priest of Cyric&lt;/a&gt; and four &lt;a href=\"Slaver%20Guard\"&gt;Slaver Guard&lt;/a&gt;s. Killing him and using his &lt;a href=\"Haegan%27s%20Key\"&gt;key&lt;/a&gt; to free the slaves on the boat is part of the requirements in completing the &lt;a href=\"Free%20Hendak%20and%20the%20slaves\"&gt;Free Hendak and the slaves&lt;/a&gt; side quest.\nMod content.\nThe &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; mod revises the captain with an SCS AI fighter script for smarter tactical combat behavior. His weapon proficiencies are flipped from the unmodded and changed to 5 pips in axe and 2 pips with two-handed sword. His primary attack method will be with Throwing Axe, where he will get off 4+ attacks per round. The captain will use his potions of \nextra healing if damaged over 50%."}
