{"id": "51255", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=51255", "title": "Cellar of Brothel", "text": "Cellar Brothel or \"Galvena's Festhall Cellar\" is an attached lengthy corridor entered from a doorway at the back of the &lt;a href=\"Brothel\"&gt;Brothel&lt;/a&gt; entrance room. \nDescription.\nThis dingy and unkept stone walled corridor is quite lengthy. It is entered from the Brothel \"front\" area, where guests are greeted and order drinks and such. Along the length of the corridor are various closed doors leading to other rooms. The look of the \"brothel\" seems more like this was Brynnlaw's armory and perhaps town jail - it certainly does not have that \"festhall\" vibe one would expect in a parlor of hedonistic pleasure.\nGameplay.\nWhen first entering the cellar from the brothel your Journal will update and display:\nThis long corridor is guarded, but the party will not be able to observe the entire length upon first entry, so they will be unseen and are located further away. With that information in mind, the party can try to find the cook to pursue the sleeping potion plot or ignore that and just rely on force of arms to explore the corridor and any various rooms connected to it by doors. If you are going to try the cook &lt;a href=\"Ellie\"&gt;Ellie&lt;/a&gt; plot - see the &lt;a href=\"Getting%20inside%20the%20asylum\"&gt;Getting inside the asylum&lt;/a&gt; page for further details.\nNo matter which way you decide to approach your goal to find &lt;a href=\"Claire\"&gt;Claire&lt;/a&gt;, you will still need to get your hands on Galvena's Key in order to open the door to the Brothel Prison area. One of the doorways on this corridor will lead to that item.\nIf the party is simply assaulting the Brothel, and or the alarm script has been initiated in the Brothel front area, then two &lt;a href=\"Guard%20%28Brothel%20Cellar%29\"&gt;Guard (Brothel Cellar)&lt;/a&gt; fighters will attack the party on sight.\nContainers.\nNone in this cellar hallway area."}
{"id": "7917", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=7917", "title": "Centeol", "text": "Centeol is a woman under a severe curse in \"&lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20%28game%29\"&gt;Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt;\" who is encountered inside the &lt;a href=\"Spider%20Nest\"&gt;spider nest&lt;/a&gt; in the area appropriately referred to as &lt;a href=\"Cloakwood%20Nest\"&gt;Cloakwood Nest&lt;/a&gt;. She has formed a significant bond with the &lt;a href=\"spiders\"&gt;spiders&lt;/a&gt; inside the nest who feed her and keep her alive. \nBackground.\nCenteol will claim that she was once a &lt;a href=\"Sorcerer\"&gt;sorceress&lt;/a&gt;, and was cursed by the arch-mage &lt;a href=\"Jon%20Irenicus\"&gt;Jon Irenicus&lt;/a&gt; for murdering his wife, &lt;a href=\"Tanova\"&gt;Lady Tanova&lt;/a&gt;. Centeol was obsessed with Irenicus and she wanted him to love her, but he loved only Tanova. So Centeol devised and executed a plan to kill her. When Irenicus discovered his wife's death, he animated her corpse (noted only in the original Baldur's Gate) and discovered the identity of her killer. Then he went to Centeol's tower and cursed her with obesity and put her in the nest with spiders to guard and feed her so she would live in misery.\nGameplay.\nHer lair must be entered by at least one member of the party in order to complete the side-quest, though killing her is not required. While she does turn hostile despite whatever dialogue choices are made, and is responsible for even more spiders joining the fight, her guardians are the real threat while she is practically harmless; she has no spells at her disposal despite a magic-intensive past, she can't move due to the curse she suffers from, and she has a very weak and slow melee attack.\nSince the nest does not require the entire party to enter, a viable tactic is to first bring in a hidden thief to chart the location of the &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Spider\"&gt;Sword Spider&lt;/a&gt;s. Then move the thief back out and bring in your tank. This will initiate the dialogue after which the tank leads one of the sword spiders outside and then just finish it off with the group. Rinse and repeat for the second sword spider. You can do the same for the &lt;a href=\"Giant%20Spider\"&gt;Giant Spider&lt;/a&gt;s and &lt;a href=\"Ettercap\"&gt;Ettercap&lt;/a&gt;s or just finish them inside. The two (hasted) sword spiders are the real threat here and because there's very little room to maneuver and they're likely to agro your weakest characters and possibly kill them before you can get the tank in melee range.\nRewards.\nKilling all creatures, including Centeol herself, yields 8100 &lt;a href=\"XP\"&gt;XP&lt;/a&gt;. Her lair also includes a treasure trove containing a &lt;a href=\"Fire%20Opal%20Ring\"&gt;Fire Opal Ring&lt;/a&gt;, a &lt;a href=\"Wand%20of%20Frost\"&gt;Wand of Frost&lt;/a&gt; with 12 charges, the cursed ring &lt;a href=\"Discipliner\"&gt;Discipliner&lt;/a&gt;, the unique two-handed sword &lt;a href=\"Spider%27s%20Bane\"&gt;Spider's Bane&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Chelak%27s%20Body\"&gt;Chelak's Body&lt;/a&gt;.\nDialogue.\nEvery dialogue option ends with her hostility and the spawning of the two giant spiders.\n\"Kill the meat, my pets.\"\nThere is an additional line, though without anything to trigger it, presumably from after the end of the fight against all of her pets:\n\"You have defeated my ssspidersss, there is nothing I can do. Kill me! Kill me!\""}
{"id": "4311", "revid": "31124876", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=4311", "title": "Central Baldur's Gate", "text": "Central Baldur's Gate is one of nine districts in the city of &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20%28city%29\"&gt;Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt;.\nReputation Trap.\nIf your Reputation is lower than 3 you will be attacked by a group of three &lt;a href=\"Flaming%20Fist%20Enforcer%20%28Baldur%27s%20Gate%29%23FLAMPUN\"&gt;Flaming Fist Enforcers&lt;/a&gt;, a &lt;a href=\"Flaming%20Fist%20Scout\"&gt;Flaming Fist Scout&lt;/a&gt; and a &lt;a href=\"Flaming%20Fist%20Battle%20Wizard\"&gt;Flaming Fist Battle Wizard&lt;/a&gt;. This group of soldiers will attack suddenly on the streets.\nTransitions.\nCity map overview.\n City grid you are at the X:\n o|o|o &lt;a href=\"Northwest%20Baldur%27s%20Gate\"&gt;NW&lt;/a&gt;|&lt;a href=\"North%20Baldur%27s%20Gate\"&gt;N&lt;/a&gt;|&lt;a href=\"Northeast%20Baldur%27s%20Gate\"&gt;NE&lt;/a&gt; \n o|X|o &lt;a href=\"West%20Baldur%27s%20Gate\"&gt;W&lt;/a&gt;|C|&lt;a href=\"East%20Baldur%27s%20Gate\"&gt;E&lt;/a&gt; \n o|o|o &lt;a href=\"Southwest%20Baldur%27s%20Gate\"&gt;SW&lt;/a&gt;|&lt;a href=\"South%20Baldur%27s%20Gate\"&gt;S&lt;/a&gt;|&lt;a href=\"Southeast%20Baldur%27s%20Gate\"&gt;SE&lt;/a&gt;"}
{"id": "55932", "revid": "55288675", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=55932", "title": "Cerebus", "text": "Cerebus is a \"Moon dog\" creature summoned forth using the &lt;a href=\"Moon%20Dog%20Figurine\"&gt;Moon Dog Figurine&lt;/a&gt; item. That item is only obtainable by the protagonist if they complete the &lt;a href=\"Ranger-Protector%20of%20the%20Umar%20Hills\"&gt;Ranger-Protector of the Umar Hills&lt;/a&gt; questline satisfactorily.\nGameplay.\nWhen the figurine is employed to summon forth Cerebus, it will appear at the location selected by the player with a summoning animation. The beast will disappear from the map in 300 game seconds (5-turns), which is plenty of time for the creature to do some good.\nCerebus is a controlled creature, as is best utilized by micromanaging its movements, selecting its targets in battle, and to give it orders to launch/cast/use its spell abilities.\nThe creature has the ability to fight in melee combat, albeit at only a moderate potential effectiveness. It can however occupy an enemy's attention and provide some potentially useful spell ability. \nAs only +2 enchanted weapons or better can strike the beast, it can be impervious against enemies that don't have that capability.\nA &lt;a href=\"Death%20Spell\"&gt;Death Spell&lt;/a&gt; will destroy/banish Cerebus, as it is a summoned creature.\nThe beast is immune to several status effects as noted on the InfoBox.\nCerebus is under a permanent Weak &lt;a href=\"Haste%20effect\"&gt;Haste effect&lt;/a&gt;, and then on top of that it has a +4 movement modifier.\nIf left to its own internal AI, Cerebus will attempt to cast or \"ApplySpell\" the innate spell abilities listed on the InfoBox.\nThe player may also command Cerebus to use its spell abilities as well, including &lt;a href=\"Healing%20Lick%20%28SPIN699%29\"&gt;Healing Lick (SPIN699)&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href=\"Moon%20Dog%20Sight%20%28SPIN696%29\"&gt;Moon Dog Sight (SPIN696)&lt;/a&gt;. \nNotes.\nCerebus' AI script is, unfortunately, not optimally written, in the sense that it assigns several actions to the dog without implementing a check to see if the player has already given it an order. This means that Cerebus will, essentially, \"fight the player\" for control for two rounds before actually obeying commands adequately. In short, it will try to, in order:\n- Cast Improved Invisibility on itself, if the one cast is still available.\n- Apply (not cast, so it doesn't waste the round's \"cast\" action) a \"free\" version of Moon Dog Howl that doesn't actually use the memorized cast, immediately upon spotting an evil enemy.\n- Cast Mirror Image on itself, if it's not already protected by it and there are enough casts left.\nAlso, it will never use Healing Lick, or Moon Dog Sight on its own, so keep that in mind.\nBeyond that, don't forget that Cerebus will try to re-cast Mirror Image on its own as soon as it expires (even if you don't want it to), so you don't ever need to order it to do that."}
{"id": "30258", "revid": "47673695", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=30258", "title": "Ceremonial Ale", "text": "The Ceremonial Ale is purchasable from &lt;a href=\"Molzahn%20of%20Tymora\"&gt;Molzahn&lt;/a&gt;, the &lt;a href=\"Halfling\"&gt;Halfling&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Cleric\"&gt;Cleric&lt;/a&gt; of &lt;a href=\"Tymora\"&gt;Tymora&lt;/a&gt; in ."}
{"id": "4581", "revid": "49127847", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=4581", "title": "Cernd", "text": "Cernd is a &lt;a href=\"male\"&gt;male&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"human\"&gt;human&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"true%20neutral\"&gt;true neutral&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"shapeshifter\"&gt;shapeshifter&lt;/a&gt; in \"&lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20II\"&gt;Baldur's Gate II&lt;/a&gt;\".\n&lt;a href=\"Gorion%27s%20Ward\"&gt;Gorion's Ward&lt;/a&gt; may choose him as a &lt;a href=\"companion\"&gt;companion&lt;/a&gt;.\nBackground.\nCernd was originally sent out to inspect the animal attacks in Trademeet, but he was caught by the townsmen while skulking around.\nRecruitment.\nCernd\u00a0is available to recruit from &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20II%20Chapter%202\"&gt;Baldur's Gate II Chapter 2&lt;/a&gt;, he will offer to join the party when talking to him in the basement of the &lt;a href=\"Mayor%27s%20House\"&gt;Mayor's House&lt;/a&gt; in &lt;a href=\"Trademeet\"&gt;Trademeet&lt;/a&gt; during the &lt;a href=\"Animal%20trouble%20in%20Trademeet\"&gt;Animal trouble in Trademeet&lt;/a&gt; sidequest. After this quest, he can be recruited again east of the ruins outside the &lt;a href=\"Druid%20Grove\"&gt;Druid Grove&lt;/a&gt; cave, where he met &lt;a href=\"Gorion%27s%20Ward\"&gt;Gorion's Ward&lt;/a&gt; to deal with the Shadow Druids for said quest.\nIn Enhanced Edition he will be level 10, Trained in Dagger, Quarterstaff, Scimitar/Wakizashi/Ninjato and Sling.\nGameplay.\nAs a &lt;a href=\"Druid%23Shapeshifter\"&gt;Shapeshifter&lt;/a&gt;, Cernd's form allows him to perform well in melee combat - due to its substantial resistances, low AC and regeneration, as well as increased &lt;a href=\"Attacks%20per%20round\"&gt;APR&lt;/a&gt; and damage. Moreover, as a Druid with a high Wisdom score (giving him several extra spell slots from levels 1-4), he can also function as a caster, should the need for it arise. Though his low Dexterity score, combined with Shapeshifter's restriction to armor usage, causes him to be quite vulnerable when out of his Werewolf forms, unless the problem is addressed with something like &lt;a href=\"Barkskin\"&gt;Barkskin&lt;/a&gt; (or &lt;a href=\"Spirit%20Armor\"&gt;Spirit Armor&lt;/a&gt;, when cast by a party member).\nWhen he joins the party, he has two items which can only be used by him: the &lt;a href=\"Staff%20of%20the%20High%20Forest\"&gt;Staff of the High Forest&lt;/a&gt;, which heals him 1 HP every 12 seconds, and the &lt;a href=\"Cloak%20of%20the%20High%20Forest\"&gt;Cloak of the High Forest&lt;/a&gt;, which improves his armor class and his saving throws by one point, like a &lt;a href=\"Cloak%20of%20Protection%20%2B1\"&gt;Cloak of Protection +1&lt;/a&gt;, however Cernd's cloak is better, in the sense that it can be worn together with a ring or an amulet of protection.\nAchievements.\nReunited.\nReunite Cernd with his estranged &lt;a href=\"Cernd%27s%20Child\"&gt;family&lt;/a&gt;."}
{"id": "40404", "revid": "47673695", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=40404", "title": "Cernd's Baby", "text": "Cernd's Baby is the child of &lt;a href=\"Cernd\"&gt;Cernd&lt;/a&gt; and is obtained from &lt;a href=\"Deril\"&gt;Deril&lt;/a&gt; in the &lt;a href=\"Deril%20Estate\"&gt;Deril Estate&lt;/a&gt; during the &lt;a href=\"Cernd%27s%20Child\"&gt;Cernd's Child&lt;/a&gt; quest."}
{"id": "5948", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=5948", "title": "Cernd's Child", "text": "Cernd's Child is a companion quest which starts when you return to &lt;a href=\"Athkatla\"&gt;Athkatla&lt;/a&gt; from &lt;a href=\"Trademeet\"&gt;Trademeet&lt;/a&gt; with &lt;a href=\"Cernd\"&gt;Cernd&lt;/a&gt; in your party. The quest will not trigger without him, obviously.\nGameplay.\nIf you've killed &lt;a href=\"Faldorn\"&gt;Faldorn&lt;/a&gt; and you have Cernd in the party, then shortly after entering any district in Athkatla, the party will be approached by &lt;a href=\"Igarol\"&gt;Igarol&lt;/a&gt;, Cernd's former neighbor, who'll mention that Cernd's wife had a child nine months after he departed to follow his call for nature. Igarol has some strong opinions about Cernd's abscence, and he and Cernd will have a lively exchange. At the end of dialogue, Cernd says \"I thank you, Igarol, even though this news is most troubling. I must speak with Galia and tell her... tell her my thoughts.\". Cernd will now want to visit his home in Waukeen's Promenade to find his wife..\nWhen the party visits &lt;a href=\"Waukeen%27s%20Promenade\"&gt;Waukeen's Promenade&lt;/a&gt; and moves to enter Cernd's former home, which is on the western side of the promenade, a beggar named &lt;a href=\"Catis\"&gt;Catis&lt;/a&gt; is within, apparently as a squatter, and will volunteer that &lt;a href=\"Fennecia\"&gt;Fennecia&lt;/a&gt;, his former servant and Nanny, may know the whereabouts of his wife. Cernd discovers that his home is unoccupied by his wife. The party must find out if Cernd's former servant and Nanny know where his wife is.\nEnter the residence to speak to Fennecia in &lt;a href=\"Fennecia%27s%20Home\"&gt;her home&lt;/a&gt; marked on your map, which is also in the promenade. Cerd will eventually say to Fennecia - \"Fennecia? Please, I have come to speak with Galia. Is she here? Our old home is deserted.\" She will tell Cernd to get out of her house, apparently, she is offended by Cernd's lack of support for his wife and child. Fennecia insists that Cernd leave.\nAfter moving Cernd out of the house, talk to Fennecia again. She will be more forthcoming with information now and tell you that Cernd's wife stayed with a noble named &lt;a href=\"Deril\"&gt;Deril&lt;/a&gt; and that she died under suspicious circumstances. She will also tell you that Cernd's child is in Deril's home. The party is going to have to investigate further and pay a visit to this estate.\nVisit the &lt;a href=\"Athkatla%20Government\"&gt;Government District&lt;/a&gt; and then move to the &lt;a href=\"Deril%20Estate\"&gt;Deril Estate&lt;/a&gt;, and when ready enter the doorway. Soon after, Cernd threatens the servant, Glut (a golem) - and &lt;a href=\"Deril\"&gt;Deril&lt;/a&gt; will appear (killing Glut for interrupting him).\nAftermath.\nIf Lagole Gon is alive, then he gives you &lt;a href=\"Cernd%27s%20Baby\"&gt;Cernd's Baby&lt;/a&gt;. If you killed Lagole Gon you can take Cernd's Baby from his corpse. If you threatened Deril, then he gives you Cernd's Baby.\nCernd (if he is still alive) will leave the party and take the child to the &lt;a href=\"Druid%20Grove%20%28cave%29\"&gt;Druid Grove&lt;/a&gt;, asking you to meet him there.\nTravel to the &lt;a href=\"Druid%20Grove\"&gt;Druid Grove&lt;/a&gt; and enter the Druid cave - Cernd leaves his baby to be raised by the druids. He will offer his services to the party once again. You may take him into the party or leave him in the grove, as the party wishes. The party could return later and ask him to join further on into the saga.\nAchievements.\nReunited.\nReunite &lt;a href=\"Cernd\"&gt;Cernd&lt;/a&gt; with his estranged family."}
