{"id": "2569", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=2569", "title": "Identify", "text": "Some special, an enchanted or cursed &lt;a href=\"item\"&gt;item&lt;/a&gt; must be identified before you can understand what they do.\nIf a character is able to \"automatically\" identify, is determined by their &lt;a href=\"lore\"&gt;lore&lt;/a&gt; \u2013 which depends on their &lt;a href=\"class\"&gt;class&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Experience%20Tables\"&gt;level&lt;/a&gt; and on their &lt;a href=\"intelligence\"&gt;intelligence&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"wisdom\"&gt;wisdom&lt;/a&gt;: &lt;a href=\"bard\"&gt;bard&lt;/a&gt;s have the highest base lore value, followed by &lt;a href=\"mage\"&gt;mage&lt;/a&gt;s, &lt;a href=\"sorcerer\"&gt;sorcerer&lt;/a&gt;s and &lt;a href=\"thieves\"&gt;thieves&lt;/a&gt;. The higher level, intelligence and wisdom, the higher lore becomes.\nIf a &lt;a href=\"party\"&gt;party&lt;/a&gt; has no character with sufficient lore to identify a specific item, a &lt;a href=\"wizard\"&gt;wizard&lt;/a&gt; can use the &lt;a href=\"spell\"&gt;spell&lt;/a&gt; \"&lt;a href=\"Identify%20%28spell%29\"&gt;Identify&lt;/a&gt;\" or its scroll for this. &lt;a href=\"Stores\"&gt;Stores&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"temples\"&gt;temples&lt;/a&gt; offer identification as a service, though for a charge.\nGameplay.\nUnidentified items will usually have a generic and usually inaccurate name, their equipped ability are constant but charge abilities are sealed until identified. Once identified, the true name and purpose of the item is revealed.\nMany items that are unidentified can't be used by a character until they are identified. For instance, a wand, potion, or scroll. Curiously, even if the party already identified an exact duplicate item previously, the game doesn't allow this knowledge to carry over and identify a duplicate automatically - thus having to identify the same item again, and again.\nSome items that are unidentified can be equipped by a character, and will confer their powers/abilities, even if not identified. This also can be potentially perilous if the item is \"cursed\".\nAs of the \"Tales of the Sword Coast\" Expansion, unidentified items will appear with a blue watermark over them in your inventory. The watermark will disappear after the identification.\nMany merchants and temples offer an identification service for a fee.\nMove the mouse/cursor over to the item displayed on the charachter record &lt;a href=\"Inventory\"&gt;Inventory&lt;/a&gt; screen and then right click, the character will try to identify the item using their &lt;a href=\"lore\"&gt;lore&lt;/a&gt;. You can also identify items with an Identify scroll or spell, or even with the &lt;a href=\"Glasses%20of%20Identification\"&gt;Glasses of Identification&lt;/a&gt;. This saves you having to locate a temple or store and saves you ."}
{"id": "30650", "revid": "3234315", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=30650", "title": "Identify (game mechanics)", "text": ""}
{"id": "4627", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=4627", "title": "Identify (spell)", "text": "The &lt;a href=\"wizard%20spell\"&gt;wizard spell&lt;/a&gt; Identify reveals all magical properties of the targeted item. It can be used if no character in the &lt;a href=\"party\"&gt;party&lt;/a&gt; has sufficient &lt;a href=\"lore\"&gt;lore&lt;/a&gt; to do so.\nGameplay.\nAn item marked as unidentified in the game that is placed anywhere in a character's record &lt;a href=\"inventory\"&gt;inventory&lt;/a&gt; will automatically be checked against the character's current &lt;a href=\"Lore\"&gt;Lore&lt;/a&gt; skill value.\nIf the Lore is sufficient, the item is identified, and thus this spell is unnecessary.\nHowever, if the lore check is insufficient, then this spell can be used instead. See the &lt;a href=\"Identify\"&gt;Identify&lt;/a&gt; mechanic process for details.\nTrivia.\nThe Advanced Dungeons and Dragons 2nd Edition Wizard spell, \"Identify\", is a very long and exhausting process in the Pen and Paper game, with quite a few rules/restrictions. The BG video game version just changed it to an instant spell that reveals the description, ID's if it's cursed, and dispensed with all of that drawn out process. It's basically completely different simplification of the Pen and Paper game's emphasis on learning complete or partial knowledge of unknown items, relics, and artifacts."}
{"id": "11600", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=11600", "title": "Idle hands in Imnesvale", "text": "Idle hands in Imnesvale is a side quest that can be acquired in the &lt;a href=\"Umar%20Hills\"&gt;Umar Hills&lt;/a&gt;.\nOverview.\n&lt;a href=\"Dirbert\"&gt;Dirbert&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Neler\"&gt;Neler&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Valsben\"&gt;Valsben&lt;/a&gt; are aspiring young adventurers, though they are too eager\u2014and far too immature\u2014to have any measure of success, but this fact is lost on them, and they insist that someone should fetch them swords and swill.\u00a0 They can be found just north of &lt;a href=\"Jermien%27s%20Home\"&gt;Jermien's Home&lt;/a&gt;.\nWalkthrough.\nDirbert will approach the nearest party member in his sight range and initiate dialogue. He and his two friends request that the party buy them some &lt;a href=\"Bastard%20Sword\"&gt;bastard swords&lt;/a&gt; and a 'keg' of &lt;a href=\"De%27Tranion%27s%20Baalor%20Ale\"&gt;De'Tranion's Baalor Ale&lt;/a&gt; to 'get them started' on their adventuring career. These youngsters are even available after their bedtime, so this encounter can occur in the dead of night as well - seems parenting is lacking for this group.\nNote that the ale can be purchased from &lt;a href=\"Min%20Minling\"&gt;Min Minling&lt;/a&gt; (you can also find some at the &lt;a href=\"Shadow%20Thief%20Guildhall\"&gt;Shadow Thief Guildhall&lt;/a&gt;) and the swords from &lt;a href=\"Elence%20Fielding\"&gt;Elence Fielding&lt;/a&gt; - these merchants are available over near the entrance to the &lt;a href=\"Imnesvale%20Inn\"&gt;Imnesvale Inn&lt;/a&gt; during daylight hours and inside the inn during the night.\nIf the party isn't interested in this, they can just reply to the request with \"Forget it boys, I've got better things to do\", and they'll complain, and that will be the end of it. However, the trio remains in the same place, should the party reconsider and initiate dialogue with them again at a later time.\nAccept the boy's request and you can promise to\nOnce the choice is made and the money received, this choice is locked in and can't be changed later.\nAt this point, you have these quest options:\nWaiting 24 hours will cause the three would-be adventurers to accuse the party of being thieves, and demand to have their gold back, thus failing the quest. The gold can then be returned, kept as a lesson for their foolishness or one can threaten them, causing them to run away.\nIf you deliver the promised swords, ale, or both, the lads will be excited, and is awarded for one item or for both. Regardless, the boys will say a few words about going adventuring and move off the area map.\nIt seems that this is the end of the quest, but there are potential additional appearances of the young trio.\nShould the party visit the &lt;a href=\"Umar%20Cave\"&gt;Umar Cave&lt;/a&gt; 24-hours after delivering the promised item(s), then they'll be encountered inside the cave.\nIf the party only provided ale to them, the lads are passed out drunk in the northern side of the cave. Speaking with Dirbert barely rouses a slurred reply, and he passes out again. That's all there is to this encounter and quest appearance.\nOn the other hand, if the party provided only swords, then inside the cave after the 24-hour period is observed some excitement from the fledgling adventurers, who are fleeing a &lt;a href=\"Shadow\"&gt;Shadow&lt;/a&gt; who is chasing them down, the boys flee the cave never to be seen in the Umar Hills again by the party.\nAnd if the party purchased them ale and swords, they'll be a bit drunk, and are fleeing a &lt;a href=\"Diseased%20Gibberling\"&gt;Diseased Gibberling&lt;/a&gt;, which they have mistakenly identified as a dragon. The bumbling fools run away never to be encountered again.\nShould the party speak with &lt;a href=\"Nelleck\"&gt;Nelleck&lt;/a&gt;, he'll delliver a scolding to the party for their irresponsibility, but otherwise face no consequences.\nJournal entries.\n\"Well, I didn't get the three kids in Imnesvale what they'd asked for. I don't need the grief I would get from their parents. I gave their money back, just to be fair.\"\n\"Well, I didn't get the three kids in Imnesvale what they'd asked for. I don't need the grief I would get from their parents. I kept their money too, just to teach the brats a lesson.\"\n\"I have, perhaps foolishly, agreed to purchase three bastard swords and some Baalor Ale for three youngsters in the village of Imnesvale. Mind you, how much trouble could they get into? One of the local merchants named Min Minling should have what they need.\"\n\"Well, I bought the three kids in Imnesvale what I promised them, and they've run off to enjoy it. Hopefully they don't get into too much trouble... and here's to hoping their parents don't get wind of this.\"\n\"Did I ask how much trouble they could get into? I just ran into the three kids from Imnesvale that I bought the ale and swords for, and they were being chased across the forest by a gibberling which they drunkenly mistook for a dragon Ah, youth...\""}
