{"id": "6889", "revid": "49135869", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=6889", "title": "Importing", "text": "In Baldur's Gate series, players may choose to start a campaign as an imported character or by transferring data from previous saves.\nTypes of import.\nCharacter import.\nIn the lower right corner of &lt;a href=\"Character%20Generation\"&gt;character generation&lt;/a&gt; screen, click \"Import\", either from \"Saved Game\" or \"Character File.\" This will bring up a list of some pre-made characters (that you can examine and select if desired) plus the ones you exported, and the ones stored in save games from previous games in the series. The \"Final Save\" of a previous game may not appear at the top of the list, and you may need to scroll down to find it.\nTo manually export a character instead, load a game, go to the the character's \"Record\" screen, there's a \"Export\" option in the lower right portion, type in the file name (this won't change the character name) which will generate a typedname.chr file in the \"characters\" subfolder located in the main folder where \".\"exe is. Each game will only read the .chr files in its own subfolder, so if you need to start Shadows of Amn with a BG1 character without importing from an existing save state, you need to manually copy paste the .chr files from BG1 to BG2 folder. You may only export the character(s) you created, &lt;a href=\"Companions\"&gt;companions&lt;/a&gt; won't be exported.\nWhile you aren't allowed to change gender, race, class, alignment, abilities, or skills of an imported character, you can still change their appearance and name, and inherit the status (eg. exp level) at the time of export. You will need to manually copy the character's portraits (in L, M and S sizes) as well as their voice pack over into the corresponding folder. You can alter these at any point during regular gameplay from the character's profile if the game doesn't automatically detect them on import.\nDepending on campaigns, you may even have all items the character themself was carrying except the . Beware though, acquiring key items this way may later cause bugs.\n&lt;a href=\"Reputation\"&gt;Reputation&lt;/a&gt; does not carry over, instead it is reset to the starting value based on &lt;a href=\"alignment\"&gt;alignment&lt;/a&gt;. Scribed spells for Mages and Bards are kept, and memorized spells are re-memorized.\nSave transfer.\nSome campaigns let you continue from previous chapters as a whole party, everything is transferred, including &lt;a href=\"romance\"&gt;romance&lt;/a&gt;s, this process happens automatically once you beat the previous chapters.\nEnhanced editions.\nTo Siege of Dragonspear.\nThere are no restrictions on the items you can import. Anything equipped or in the inventory of your created characters (including containers), anything in the inventory of non-SOD NPCs in your party, and anything equipped or in the inventory of SOD NPCs will be imported if you continue a game from Baldur's Gate. This means when you later meet a BG:EE NPC, such as Edwin they will have all the equipment and inventory items that they had on them at the point you finished BG:EE, even if they were not in your party at the time. Non-SOD NPCs in your party at the end of BG:EE will be replaced by a SOD NPC of a similar alignment; however, they will only have generic starting equipment. When you get to your chest in the Ducal Palace you will find the items from the inventory of the Non-SOD NPCs that were in your party (as well as all of &lt;a href=\"Imoen\"&gt;Imoen&lt;/a&gt;'s inventory in a separate chest), but none of the items they had equipped.\nYou will lose any Gold Pieces you had at the end of BG:EE, so convert your GP to items. To bring the maximum number of items into SOD, fill all containers (Potion Case, Scroll Case, Gem Bag, Bag of Holding). Fully equip all SOD NPCs before the final battle, including quiver, quick items and inventory, but do not have any of those NPCs in your party. If you have a party of Non-SOD NPCs make sure you put all their equipment into their inventory. You do not need to worry about doing that for any custom characters you have in your party. Some SOD NPCs cannot be recruited, so you will either need to pick pocket the items from them or kill them.\nIf you intend on continuing with your characters into SOA you may want to prioritize having three or four of the items listed below in your inventory."}
